oracle.iam.identity.icf.connector.openfire.security

Class Blowfish

  • java.lang.Object
    • oracle.iam.identity.icf.connector.openfire.security.Blowfish
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Encryptor

    public class Blowfish
extends java.lang.Object
implements Encryptor
    Provides static methods symmetric Blowfish encryption/decryption.

    To strengthen the encrypted result, use the seed(java.lang.String) method to provide a custom key prior to invoking the encrypt(java.lang.String, byte[]) or decrypt(java.lang.String, byte[]) methods. Blowfish is a symmetric-key block cipher, designed in 1993 by Bruce Schneier and included in many cipher suites and encryption products. Blowfish provides a good encryption rate in software, and no effective cryptanalysis of it has been found to date. However, the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) now receives more attention, and Schneier recommends Twofish for modern applications.

    Schneier designed Blowfish as a general-purpose algorithm, intended as an alternative to the aging DES and free of the problems and constraints associated with other algorithms. At the time Blowfish was released, many other designs were proprietary, encumbered by patents or were commercial or government secrets. Schneier has stated that:
    "Blowfish is unpatented, and will remain so in all countries. The algorithm is hereby placed in the public domain, and can be freely used by anyone."
    See Description of a New Variable-Length Key, 64-Bit Block Cipher (Blowfish)
